{{EngvarB|date=October 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Linda Aronson | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|3|20|df=y}} | birth_place = United Kingdom | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | body_discovered = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | nationality = Australian | other_names = | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = Screenwriter, author | years_active = 1979–present | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = | notable_works = ''[[Kostas (film)|Kostas]]'' | style = | influences = | influenced = | home_town = | television = | spouse = | awards = }} '''Linda Aronson''' (born 20 March 1950) is a British-born Australian [[screenwriter]], educator and author. She wrote the [[Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts|AACTA]]-nominated drama ''[[Kostas (film)|Kostas]]'' and several television series, such as ''[[Something in the Air]]'' and ''[[G.P.]]''.<ref>[http://www.aacta.org/winners-nominees/1970-1979/1979.aspx AACTA]</ref><ref>[http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/A157?mainTabTemplate=agentWorksBy Austlit]</ref>
Born in [[London]], Aronson moved out to [[Essex]] at a young age. She studied at [[Ulster University]], then did late nineteenth century fiction at [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]], but abandoned it to pursue a career as a writer. Her first paid writing job was a 1973 radio adaptation of her own [[Play (theatre)|stage play]], ''Closing Down'' for ABC. This was followed by ''Cafe in a Side Street'' in 1975, and ''The Fall Guy'' in 1976. The latter success lead to her writing ''Kostas''.<ref>[http://adelaidescreenwriter.blogspot.com/2013/01/an-interview-with-linda-aronson.html Adelaide Screenwriter Interview]</ref>
== ''The 21st Century Screenplay'' == Aronson is also a prolific author, having written several books including the screenwriting guide ''The 21st Century Screenplay.'' The book was written as a response to standard screenwriting teaching that focused on linear, single protagonist stories. Aronsson, instead, discusses how to write for non-linear stories with multiple characters.<ref>http://www.lindaaronson.com/21st-century-screenplay.html</ref><ref>https://scriptangel.com/writing-non-linear-flashback-and-ensemble-scripts-by-linda-aronson/</ref><ref>https://www.livingspiritgroup.com/podcasts/vodcasts/linda-aronson/</ref><ref>https://www.networkisa.org/modules/curious/view/writing-non-linear-and-ensembles-for-film-and-tv-with-linda-aronson</ref>
